In 1828 the [U.S. government](/Federal_Government_of_the_United_States) purchased the land encompassing the Naval Live Oaks Reservation for experimenting with acorns for the cultivation of live oaks to produce wooden ships. Before the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War), the wood of the [live oak](/Live_oak) was the primary material of choice for shipbuilders, thus the protection and cultivation of the trees for the [United States Navy](/United_States_Navy) was considered vital for defense in those turbulent times. Currently, the land comprises over 1,300 acres (530&#160;ha) in [Gulf Islands National Seashore](/Gulf_Islands_National_Seashore) and is supervised by the [National Park Service](/National_Park_Service). To the south of Highway 98 is a visitor center for the Gulf Islands National Seashore and several public beach areas.

